Definition 4.0.3 (Final functors). We say a functor $f:K\to K^{\prime}$ between $\infty$-categories is final (or left final when seeking to further avoid ambiguity) if for any functor $G:K^{\prime}\to\mathcal{C}$, restriction along $f$ preserves colimits. More precisely, denoting $(K^{\prime})^{\triangleright}$ by the $\infty$-category obtained by affixing a terminal object to $K^{\prime}$, $f$ is final if and only if the restriction map $f^{*}:\mathcal{F}\mathsf{un}((K^{\prime})^{\triangleright},\mathcal{C})\to% \mathcal{F}\mathsf{un}(K^{\triangleright},\mathcal{C})$ sends colimit diagrams to colimit diagrams. Dually, we call $f$ initial, or right initial, if and only if the restriction map $f^{*}:\mathcal{F}\mathsf{un}((K^{\prime})^{\triangleleft},\mathcal{C})\to% \mathcal{F}\mathsf{un}(K^{\triangleleft},\mathcal{C})$ sends limit diagrams to limit diagrams.
Definition 6.1.2. Let $I$ be a paracyclic preorder and let $\mathsf{Arr}(I)$ denote the set of all pairs $(i,j)\in I$ such that $i\leq j$. We let $F^{(I)}\subset(-\infty,\infty]^{\mathsf{Arr}I}$ denote the set of those $\alpha$ satisfying the following conditions: (1) $\alpha(i,i)=0$. (2) $\alpha(i,j)+\alpha(j,k)=\alpha(i,k)$ for all $i\leq j\leq k\in I$, (3) $\alpha(i,j)=\alpha(i+1,j+1)$ for all $i\leq j\in I$, and (4) $\alpha(i,i+1)=\infty$. We endow $F^{(I)}$ with the topology inherited from the usual topology on the infinite product $(-\infty,\infty]^{\mathsf{Arr}(I)}$.
Definition 10.2.6. $\mathsf{Broken}_{\operatorname{cyc}}$ is the stack classifying families of broken cycles.
Definition 5.2.4. We let $\mathsf{PreOrd_{\mathbb{Z}}}$ denote the category whose objects are (countable) $\mathbb{Z}$-equivariant linear preorders, and whose morphisms are $\mathbb{Z}$-equivariant maps $r:I\to J$ weakly preserving $\leq$, and which are essentially surjective. We let $\mathsf{PreOrd_{\circlearrowleft}}\subset\mathsf{PreOrd_{\mathbb{Z}}}$ denote the full subcategory whose objects are paracyclic preorders.
Definition 10.1.4. Fix an $\infty$-category $\mathcal{C}$. A cyclic object in $\mathcal{C}$ is a functor $\Delta_{\operatorname{cyc}}^{\operatorname{op}}\to\mathcal{C}.$ A semicyclic object is the data of a functor $(\Delta_{\operatorname{cyc}}^{\operatorname{inj}})^{\operatorname{op}}\to% \mathcal{C}$ where $\Delta_{\operatorname{cyc}}^{\operatorname{inj}}\subset\Delta_{\operatorname{% cyc}}$ consists of those morphisms arising from injective morphisms in $\Delta_{\circlearrowleft}$.
Definition 3.0.5. A broken paracycle is the data of a topological space $L$ equipped with a continuous action of $\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{R}$ satisfying the following properties: (L1) $L$ is abstractly homeomorphic to $(-\infty,\infty)$ as a topological space. (L2) The $\mathbb{Z}=\mathbb{Z}\times\{0\}$ action is free. (L3) The $\mathbb{R}=\{0\}\times\mathbb{R}$ action is directed. That is, there exists a homeomorphism $L\cong(-\infty,\infty)$ so that the induced action on $(-\infty,\infty)$ satisfies $t\cdot x\geq x$ for all $t\geq 0\in\mathbb{R}$. We let $\leq_{L}$ denote the order on $L$ induced from the standard order on $(-\infty,\infty)$. (L4) The $\mathbb{Z}=\mathbb{Z}\times\{0\}$ action is compatibly directed. That is, for any $x\in L$, we have $x\leq_{L}x+1$. (Here, $+1$ is the action by $1\in\mathbb{Z}$.) (L5) The fixed point set $L^{\mathbb{R}}$ is discrete and non-empty.
Definition 8.3.3. We call the stratification $|\Delta^{n}|\to[n]$ from Construction 8.3.1 the standard stratification on the $n$-simplex.
Definition 5.2.1. Recall that a preorder $(I,\leq_{I})$ is a set $I$ equipped with a relation $\leq\subset I\times I$ such that for any $i\in I$ we have $i\leq i$, and for any triplet $i,j,k\in I$, we have that $i\leq j\leq k\implies i\leq k$. A preorder is called linear if for any pair $i,j\in I$, we have $i\leq j$ or $j\leq i$ (or both). A $\mathbb{Z}$-equivariant linear preorder is a countable, linear preorder $I$ equipped with a free, relation-preserving $\mathbb{Z}$-action $\mathbb{Z}\times I\to I$. That is, • $i\leq j\implies i+1\leq j+1$. • $i\leq i+1$. Finally, a paracyclic preorder is a $\mathbb{Z}$-equivariant preorder $I$ such that • For any $i\in I$, $i$ is strictly less than $i+1$. That is, $i\leq i+1$, but $i+1\not\leq i$.
Definition 10.1.1. The cyclic category $\Delta_{\operatorname{cyc}}$ is the category with the same objects as $\Delta_{\circlearrowleft}$, and where we set $\hom_{\Delta_{\operatorname{cyc}}}(I,J)=\hom_{\Delta_{\circlearrowleft}}(I,J)/% \mathbb{Z}$ with the inherited composition law.
Definition 2.0.4. If $\mathcal{C}$ is an $\infty$-category, a paracyclic object of $\mathcal{C}$ is a functor $\Delta_{\circlearrowleft}^{\operatorname{op}}\to\mathcal{C}$. Let $\Delta_{\circlearrowleft}^{\operatorname{inj}}\subset\Delta_{\circlearrowleft}$ denote the subcategory consisting of injective maps. A semiparacyclic object is a functor $(\Delta_{\circlearrowleft}^{\operatorname{inj}})^{\operatorname{op}}\to% \mathcal{C}$.
Definition 8.2.3 (Conical stratification). Let $X\to P$ be a stratified space and fix $x\in X$ with image $p_{x}\in P$. We say $X$ is conically stratified at $x$ if there exists an open subset $U\subset X$ containing $x$ which is homeomorphic to $Z\times C(Y)$ where (1) $Z$ is a topological space, (2) $Y$ is a $P_{>p_{x}}$-stratified space (see Notation 8.1.3), (3) $C(Y)=Y\times[0,\infty)/Y\times\{0\}$ is the open cone on $Y$, stratified by the poset $P_{>p_{x}}\cup p_{x}=P_{\geq p_{x}}$ by sending $[(y,0)]\mapsto p_{x}$, and (4) $Z\times C(Y)$ is the stratified space whose stratification is the composition $Z\times C(Y)\to C(Y)\to P_{\geq p_{x}}$. We say $X$ is conically stratified if it is conically stratified at $x$ for every $x\in X$.
Definition 4.1.6. Dually, a right Kan extension is a pair $(j_{*}F,\epsilon)$ where $\epsilon:j_{*}F\circ j\to F$ is a natural transformation, and the pair is terminal among such data. Or, letting $j^{\operatorname{op}}:\mathcal{C}^{\operatorname{op}}\to\mathcal{D}^{% \operatorname{op}}$ and $F^{\operatorname{op}}:\mathcal{C}^{\operatorname{op}}\to\mathcal{E}^{% \operatorname{op}}$ be the induced functors on opposite categories, the right Kan extension may be expressed as a left Kan extension: $j_{*}F=((j^{\operatorname{op}})_{!}F^{\operatorname{op}})^{\operatorname{op}}.$
Definition 8.5.3. Let $X$ be a topological space, and let $p:X\to\ast$ be the constant map to a point. A sheaf on $X$ is called constant if it is in the essential image of the pullback functor $p^{*}:\mathcal{S}\mathsf{hv}(\ast)\to\mathcal{S}\mathsf{hv}(X).$ Equivalently, we say a sheaf $\mathcal{F}$ is constant if there exists an object $A\in\mathcal{C}$ and a map from $A$ to the global sections $\mathcal{F}(X)$ such that, for any $x\in X$, the composite map $A\to\mathcal{F}(X)\to\mathcal{F}_{x}$ to the stalk is an equivalence.
Definition 3.1.1 (Family of broken paracycles). Fix $S$ a topological space. A family of broken paracycles over $S$ is the data of $(\pi:L_{S}\to S,\mu:(\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{R})\times L_{S}\to L_{S})$ where $L_{S}$ is a topological space, $\pi$ is a continuous map, and $\mu$ is a continuous $\mathbb{Z}\times\mathbb{R}$-action on $L_{S}$ preserving the fibers, such that (Q1) For every $s\in S$, $\mu$ renders the fiber $L_{s}:=\pi^{-1}(s)$ a broken paracycle (Definition 3.0.5). (Q2) Let $L_{S}^{\mathbb{R}}$ denote the fixed point set of the $\mathbb{R}=\{0\}\times\mathbb{R}$ action. Then the map $L_{S}^{\mathbb{R}}\to S$ induced by $\pi$ is unramified modulo $\mathbb{Z}$. (See Remark 3.1.3 below.) (Q3) The induced projection from the quotient space $L_{S}/\mathbb{Z}\to S$ is a closed map. (See also Proposition 3.2.5 below.) (Q4) The set $\{(x,y)\text{ such that $x\leq y$}\}$ is a closed subset of the fiber product $L_{S}\times_{S}L_{S}$. (Q5) Let $L_{S}^{\circ}=L_{S}\setminus L_{S}^{\mathbb{R}}$ be the complement of the fixed point set. Then the map $L_{S}^{\circ}\to S$ induced by $\pi$ has the local lifting property.
Definition 5.5.1. Fix two $\mathbb{Z}$-equivariant preorders $I$ and $J$. An amalgam of $I$ and $J$ is a $\mathbb{Z}$-equivariant preorder $K$ equipped with a weakly order-preserving, $\mathbb{Z}$-equivariant injection $I\coprod J\to K$. Fixing $I$ and $J$, we let $\mathsf{Amalg}(I,J)$ denote the category of amalgams of $I$ and $J$. For convenience, we will model $\mathsf{Amalg}(I,J)$ as a poset as follows: We restrict attention to those $K$ whose underlying set is equal to $I\coprod J$, and the map $I\coprod J\to K$ is the identity on underlying sets. The poset structure is obtained by declaring $K\leq K^{\prime}$ if and only if $\leq_{K}\subset\leq_{K^{\prime}}$; i.e., if and only if $x\leq_{K}y\implies x\leq_{K^{\prime}}y$.
Definition 10.2.3. Fix a topological space $S$ and a pair $(\pi:C_{S}\to S,\mu)$ where $\mu$ is a fiber-wise $\mathbb{R}$-action on $C_{S}$. We say $(\pi:C_{S}\to S,\mu)$ is a family of broken cycles if and only if it satisfies the following: (1) (Fibers are broken cycles.) For every $s\in S$, the fiber $C_{s}=\pi^{-1}(s)$ is a broken cycle in the sense of Definition 10.2.1. (2) (Unramified.) Let $C_{S}^{\mathbb{R}}$ denote the fixed point set of the $\mathbb{R}$-action. Then the map $C_{S}^{\mathbb{R}}\to S$ induced by $\pi$ is unramified. (3) (Local triviality.) For every $s\in S$, there is an open subset $U\subset S$ containing $s$ such that there exists an orientation-preserving homeomorphism $U\times S^{1}\cong\pi^{-1}(U)$ which respects the projection to $U$.
Definition A.13. Let $(X,\Sigma,\mu)$ and $(Y,\Omega,\nu)$ be two measure spaces. Two transition kernels $f,g:X\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09){% \hole}};\endxy\!Y$ are said to be $\mu$-a.e. equivalent, written as $f\underset{\raisebox{2.58pt}[0.0pt][0.0pt]{\scriptsize$\mu$}}{=}g,$ iff for each $F\in\Omega,$ there exists a measurable set $N_{F}\in\Sigma$ such that $f_{x}(F)=g_{x}(F)\quad\forall\;x\in X\setminus N_{F}\qquad\text{and}\qquad\mu(% N_{F})=0.$
Definition 3.16. Let ${{\mathcal{A}}}$ and ${{\mathcal{B}}}$ be $C^{*}$-algebras, let $F,F^{\prime}:{{\mathcal{B}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{% ~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathcal{A}}}$ be two linear maps, and let $\omega:{{\mathcal{A}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"% 1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathbb{C}}}$ be a state (or more generally a positive linear functional) on ${{\mathcal{A}}}.$ Let $\mathcal{N}_{\omega}:=\big{\{}a\in{{\mathcal{A}}}\;:\;\omega(a^{*}a)=0\big{\}}$ denote the null space of $\omega.$ Since $\mathcal{N}_{\omega}$ is a left ideal of ${{\mathcal{A}}}$ (see Construction 3.1 in [PaGNS] for details) denote the quotient vector space by ${{\mathcal{A}}}/\mathcal{N}_{\omega}.$ $F$ and $F^{\prime}$ are said to be equal almost everywhere (a.e.) with respect to $\omega$ or equal $\omega$-a.e. iff the diagram (in the category of vector spaces and linear maps) $\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(15,0)*+{{{\mathcal{A}}}/\mathcal{N}_{\omega}}="AN";(-15,0)*+{{% {\mathcal{B}}}}="B";(0,7.5)*+{{{\mathcal{A}}}}="AF";(0,-7.5)*+{{{\mathcal{A}}}% }="AG";{\ar@{~{}>}"B";"AF"^{F}};{\ar@{~{}>}"B";"AG"_{F^{\prime}}};{\ar@{->>}"% AF";"AN"};{\ar@{->>}"AG";"AN"};\endxy$ commutes, i.e. iff $F(b)-F^{\prime}(b)\in\mathcal{N}_{\omega}$ for all $b\in{{\mathcal{B}}}.$ The two maps ${{\mathcal{A}}}\twoheadrightarrow{{\mathcal{A}}}/\mathcal{N}_{\omega}$ in (3.18) are the quotient maps of ${{\mathcal{A}}}$ onto ${{\mathcal{A}}}/\mathcal{N}_{\omega}.$ When $F$ and $F^{\prime}$ are equal a.e. with respect to $\omega,$ the notation $F\underset{\raisebox{2.58pt}[0.0pt][0.0pt]{\scriptsize$\omega$}}{=}F^{\prime}$ will be used.
Definition 6.45. Let ${{\mathcal{B}}}\subseteq{{\mathcal{A}}}$ be $C^{*}$-subalgebra of a $C^{*}$-algebra ${{\mathcal{A}}}.$ A conditional expectation is a positive unital map ${{\mathcal{A}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-5,0)*{}="1";(5,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|% (1.09){\hole}^{E}};\endxy\!{{\mathcal{B}}}$ such that $E(AB)=E(A)B$ for all $A\in{{\mathcal{A}}}$ and $B\in{{\mathcal{B}}}$.
Definition 2.16. Let $X$ and $Y$ be finite sets and let $p$ be a probability measure on $X.$ Let $N_{p}:=\{x\in X\;:\;p_{x}=0\}$ denote the null-set of $(X,p).$ Two stochastic maps $f,g:X\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09){% \hole}};\endxy\!Y$ are $p$-a.e. equivalent iff $\big{\{}x\in X\;:\;f(x)\neq g(x)\big{\}}\subseteq N_{p}.$ The notation $f\underset{\raisebox{2.58pt}[0.0pt][0.0pt]{\scriptsize$p$}}{=}g$ is used whenever $f$ and $g$ are $p$-a.e. equivalent. Here, $f(x)\neq g(x)$ means $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ are different measures on $Y,$ i.e. there exists a $y\in Y$ such that $f_{yx}\neq g_{yx}.$
Definition B.14. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category and let $\mathcal{T}:=(T,b,\delta)$ be a monad on $\mathcal{C}.$ The Kleisli category associated to the monad $(T,b,\delta)$ is the category $\mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{T}}$ defined as follows. The objects of $\mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{T}}$ are the objects of $\mathcal{C}.$ A morphism from an object $a$ to an object $b$ in $\mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{T}}$ is denoted by $a\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}}% ;\endxy\!b$ and is a morphism $a\to T(b)$ in $\mathcal{C}.$ The composition $a\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-5,0)*{}="1";(5,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}^% {f}};\endxy\!b\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-5,0)*{}="1";(5,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(% 1.09){\hole}^{g}};\endxy\!c$ of morphisms in $\mathcal{C}_{\mathcal{T}}$ is defined as the composition $a\xrightarrow{f}T(b)\xrightarrow{T(g)}T(T(c))\xrightarrow{b_{c}}T(c)$ in $\mathcal{C}.$ The identity morphism $a\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-5,0)*{}="1";(5,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}^% {\mathrm{id}_{a}}};\endxy\!a$ is defined to be the morphism $a\xrightarrow{\delta_{a}}T(a).$
