Definition 3.6. Let ${{\mathcal{A}}}$ and ${{\mathcal{B}}}$ be $C^{*}$-algebras. Given $n\in{{\mathbb{N}}},$ a linear map $\varphi:{{\mathcal{B}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}% "1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathcal{A}}}$ is $n$-positive iff $\mathrm{id}_{\mathcal{M}_{n}({{\mathbb{C}}})}\otimes\varphi:\mathcal{M}_{n}({{% \mathbb{C}}})\otimes{{\mathcal{B}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2"% ;{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!\mathcal{M}_{n}({{\mathbb{C}}})% \otimes{{\mathcal{A}}}$ is positive. $\varphi$ is completely positive iff $\varphi$ is $n$-positive for all $n\in{{\mathbb{N}}}.$ A completely positive (unital) map will be abbreviated as a CP (CPU) map.
Definition A.1. Let $(X,\Sigma)$ and $(Y,\Omega)$ be measurable spaces. A transition kernel $r$ from $(Y,\Omega)$ to $(X,\Sigma)$, written $r:Y\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09){\hole% }};\endxy\!X,$ is a function $r:Y\times\Sigma\to[0,\infty]$ such that i. $r(y,\;\cdot\;):\Sigma\to[0,\infty]$ is a measure for all $y\in Y$ and ii. $r(\;\cdot\;,E):Y\to[0,\infty]$ is measurable for all $E\in\Sigma.$ The notation $r_{y}(E):=r(y,E)$ will be implemented.
Definition 2.10. Let $X,Y,$ and $Z$ be finite sets. The composition of the stochastic map $f:X\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09){\hole% }};\endxy\!Y$ followed by the stochastic map $g:Y\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09){\hole% }};\endxy\!Z,$ written as $g\circ f:X\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09% ){\hole}};\endxy\!Z,$ is the function $g\circ f:X\to\mathrm{PM}(Z)$ defined by sending $x\in X$ to the probability measure on $Z$ determined by $\begin{split}\displaystyle Z\ni z\xmapsto{(g\circ f)(x)}(g\circ f)_{zx}:=\sum_% {y\in Y}g_{zy}f_{yx}.\end{split}$
Definition B.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a category and let $c$ be an object of $\mathcal{C}.$ The over category $c/\mathcal{C}$ and under category $\mathcal{C}/c$ are defined as follows. An object of $c/\mathcal{C}$ consists of a pair $(a,p)$ with $a$ an object of $\mathcal{C}$ and $p$ a morphism $c\xrightarrow{p}a$ in $\mathcal{C}.$ A morphism from $(a,c\xrightarrow{p}a)$ to $(b,c\xrightarrow{q}b)$ in $c/\mathcal{C}$ is a morphism $a\xrightarrow{f}b$ in $\mathcal{C}$ such that the diagram $\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(0,7.5)*+{c}="c";(-10,-7.5)*+{a}="a";(10,-7.5)*+{b}="b";{\ar"c"% ;"a"_{p}};{\ar"c";"b"^{q}};{\ar"a";"b"_{f}};\endxy$ commutes. The composition of morphisms in $c/\mathcal{C}$ is defined by the composition of morphisms in $\mathcal{C}.$ As a result, a morphism $(a,c\xrightarrow{p}a)\xrightarrow{f}(b,c\xrightarrow{q}b)$ in $c/\mathcal{C}$ will often be denoted by the commutative diagram (B.2) in $\mathcal{C}.$ Similarly, an object of $\mathcal{C}/c$ consists of a pair $(a,j)$ with $a$ an object of $\mathcal{C}$ and $j$ a morphism $a\xrightarrow{j}c$ in $\mathcal{C}.$ A morphism from $(a,a\xrightarrow{j}c)$ to $(b,b\xrightarrow{k}c)$ in $\mathcal{C}/c$ is a morphism $a\xrightarrow{f}b$ in $\mathcal{C}$ such that the diagram $\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(0,-7.5)*+{c}="c";(-10,7.5)*+{a}="a";(10,7.5)*+{b}="b";{\ar"a";% "c"_{j}};{\ar"b";"c"^{k}};{\ar"a";"b"^{f}};\endxy$ commutes. As a result, a morphism $(a,a\xrightarrow{j}c)\xrightarrow{f}(b,b\xrightarrow{k}c)$ in $\mathcal{C}/c$ will often be denoted by the commutative diagram (B.3) in $\mathcal{C}.$
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathcal{H}$ and $\mathcal{K}$ be two Hilbert spaces. A density matrix $\rho$ on $\mathcal{H}\otimes\mathcal{K}$ is said to be separable with respect to $\mathcal{H}$ and $\mathcal{K}$ iff there exist a natural number $n\in{{\mathbb{N}}},$ a collection of density matrices $\{\rho_{i}^{{{\mathcal{H}}}}\}_{i\in\{1,...,n\}}$ on ${{\mathcal{H}}}$ and $\{\rho_{i}^{{{\mathcal{K}}}}\}_{i\in\{1,...,n\}}$ on ${{\mathcal{K}}},$ and strictly positive numbers $\{\lambda_{i}\}_{i\in\{1,...,n\}}$ such that $\rho=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\lambda_{i}\rho_{i}^{{{\mathcal{H}}}}\otimes\rho_{i}^{{{% \mathcal{K}}}}.$ $\rho$ is said to be entangled with respect to ${{\mathcal{H}}}$ and ${{\mathcal{K}}}$ iff no such decomposition exists.4Entanglement highly depends on the choice of Hilbert space decomposition (see Kil-Chan Ha’s work for an interesting example [Ha10]).
