Definition 2.1. Let $X$ and $Y$ be two finite sets (equipped with the discrete $\sigma$-algebra). Let $\mathrm{PM}(Y)$ denote the set of probability measures on $Y.$ A stochastic map from $X$ to $Y$ is a function $\begin{split}\displaystyle X&\displaystyle\xrightarrow{f}\mathrm{PM}(Y)\\ \displaystyle x&\displaystyle\mapsto f(x)\end{split}$ whose evaluation on subsets of $Y$ is written as $Y\supseteq E\xmapsto{f(x)}f_{x}(E)\in{{\mathbb{R}}}_{\geq 0}.$
Definition 3.34. Using the same notation from Lemma 3.32, $P_{\omega}$ is called the support of $\omega$. Its complement will occasionally be denoted by $P_{\omega}^{\perp}:=1_{{{\mathcal{A}}}}-P_{\omega}.$
Definition A.25. Let $(X,\Sigma,\mu)$ and $(Y,\Omega,\nu)$ be measure spaces and let $f:X\to Y$ be a measure-preserving map. A regular conditional probability is a transition kernel $r:Y\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|(1.09){\hole% }};\endxy\!X$ for which there exists a $\nu$-null set $N\in\Omega$ such that $r_{y}$ is a probability measure for all $y\in Y\setminus N$ and $\mu\big{(}E\cap f^{-1}(F)\big{)}=\int_{F}r_{y}(E)\;d\nu(y)\qquad\forall\;E\in% \Sigma\text{ and }\forall\;F\in\Omega.$
Definition 3.134. Given a commutative diagram $\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(0,-7.5)*+{{{\mathbb{C}}}}="C";(-12.5,7.5)*+{{{\mathcal{A}}}}="% H";(12.5,7.5)*+{{{\mathcal{B}}}}="K";{\ar@{~{}>}"H";"C"_{\omega}};{\ar@{~{}>}"% K";"C"^{\xi}};{\ar"K";"H"_{F}};\endxy$ of CPU maps on finite-dimensional $C^{*}$-algebras, a hypothesis for (3.135) is a positive unital map $R:{{\mathcal{A}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2% "|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathcal{B}}}$ such that $\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(0,-7.5)*+{{{\mathcal{A}}}}="C";(-10,7.5)*+{{{\mathcal{B}}}}="H% ";(10,7.5)*+{{{\mathcal{B}}}}="K";{\ar"H";"C"_{F}};{\ar@{~{}>}"C";"K"_{R}};{% \ar"H";"K"^{\mathrm{id}_{{{\mathcal{B}}}}}};\endxy\quad\text{commutes $\xi$-a.% e., i.e. }\quad R\circ F\underset{\raisebox{2.58pt}[0.0pt][0.0pt]{\scriptsize$% \xi$}}{=}\mathrm{id}_{{{\mathcal{B}}}}.$ A hypothesis for (3.135) is optimal iff $\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(0,-7.5)*+{{{\mathbb{C}}}}="C";(-10,7.5)*+{{{\mathcal{A}}}}="H"% ;(10,7.5)*+{{{\mathcal{B}}}}="K";{\ar@{~{}>}"H";"C"_{\omega}};{\ar@{~{}>}"K";"% C"^{\xi}};{\ar@{~{}>}"H";"K"^{R}};\endxy\quad\text{commutes, i.e. }\quad\xi% \circ R=\omega.$ A disintegration of $\omega$ over $\xi$ is a positive unital map $R:{{\mathcal{A}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2% "|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathcal{B}}}$ s.t. (3.137) holds. A disintegration of $\omega$ over $\xi$ consistent with $F$ is a disintegration of $\omega$ over $\xi$ s.t. (3.136) holds. The adjective “CPU” is appended when the disintegration $R$ is completely positive and unital.
Definition 3.1. A $C^{*}$-algebra is an algebra ${{\mathcal{A}}}$ equipped with a unit $1_{{{\mathcal{A}}}},$ an involution ${}^{*}:{{\mathcal{A}}}\to{{\mathcal{A}}}$, and a norm $\lVert\;\cdot\;\rVert:{{\mathcal{A}}}\to{{\mathbb{R}}}$ such that it is a ${}^{*}$-algebra, it is closed with respect to the topology induced by its norm, and it satisfies the $C^{*}$-identity, which says $\lVert a^{*}a\rVert=\lVert a\rVert^{2}$ for all $a\in{{\mathcal{A}}}.$ Given a $C^{*}$-algebra ${{\mathcal{A}}},$ a positive element of ${{\mathcal{A}}}$ is an element $a\in{{\mathcal{A}}}$ for which there exists an $x\in{{\mathcal{A}}}$ such that $a=x^{*}x.$ The set of positive elements in ${{\mathcal{A}}}$ is denoted by ${{\mathcal{A}}}^{+}.$ Given another $C^{*}$-algebra ${{\mathcal{B}}},$ a positive map $\varphi:{{\mathcal{B}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}% "1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathcal{A}}}$ is a linear map such that $\varphi({{\mathcal{B}}}^{+})\subseteq{{\mathcal{A}}}^{+}.$ A linear map $\varphi:{{\mathcal{B}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}% "1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathcal{A}}}$ is unital iff $\varphi(1_{{{\mathcal{B}}}})=1_{{{\mathcal{A}}}}.$ A state on a $C^{*}$-algebra ${{\mathcal{A}}}$ is a positive linear unital functional $\omega:{{\mathcal{A}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"% 1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathbb{C}}}.$ A ${}^{*}$-homomorphism from ${{\mathcal{A}}}$ to ${{\mathcal{B}}}$ is a function $f:{{\mathcal{A}}}\to{{\mathcal{B}}}$ preserving the $C^{*}$-algebra structure, namely $f$ is linear, $f$ is a homomorphism $f(aa^{\prime})=f(a)f(a^{\prime}),$ $f$ is unital $f(1_{{{\mathcal{A}}}})=1_{{{\mathcal{B}}}},$ and $f(a^{*})=f(a)^{*}$ for all $a,a^{\prime}\in{{\mathcal{A}}}.$ If $\omega:{{\mathcal{A}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"% 1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathbb{C}}}$ and $\xi:{{\mathcal{B}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";% "2"|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathbb{C}}}$ are states, then a linear map $\varphi:{{\mathcal{B}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}% "1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathcal{A}}}$ is said to be state-preserving whenever $\varphi\circ\omega=\xi.$
Definition 6.50. Let ${{\mathcal{B}}}\subseteq{{\mathcal{A}}}$ be $C^{*}$-subalgebra of a $C^{*}$-algebra ${{\mathcal{A}}}$ and let $\omega:{{\mathcal{A}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-3,0)*{}="1";(3,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"% 1";"2"|(1.09){\hole}};\endxy\!{{\mathbb{C}}}$ be a state. A conditional expectation ${{\mathcal{A}}}\;\xy 0;/r.25pc/:(-5,0)*{}="1";(5,0)*{}="2";{\ar@{~{}>}"1";"2"|% (1.09){\hole}^{E}};\endxy\!{{\mathcal{B}}}$ leaves the state $\omega$ invariant iff $\omega\big{(}E(A)\big{)}=\omega(A)$ for all $A\in{{\mathcal{A}}}$.
Definition 5.3. Let $X$ be a topological space. A pre-pseudogroup on $X$ is a triple of a small category $\mathcal{C}$, an embedding functor $X_{top}\subset\mathcal{C}$ and a functor $\mathcal{C}\rightarrow Homeo^{l}_{X};f\mapsto\bar{f}$ satisfying the following: (1) $Ob(X_{top})=Ob(\mathcal{C})=Ob(Homeo^{l}_{X})$. (2) the composition $X_{top}\subset\mathcal{C}\rightarrow Homeo^{l}_{X}$ coinsides with the inclusion $X_{top}\subset Homeo^{l}_{X}$. (3) the category $\mathcal{C}^{\star}$ is a groupoid, where $\mathcal{C}^{\star}(x,y)\overset{\mathrm{def}}{=}\{f_{x}\in\mathcal{C}_{x}(X)|% \bar{f}(x)=y\}$ A pseudogroup sheaf on $X$ is a pre-pseudogroup on $X$ satisfying the following: (4) the pre-sheaf $\mathcal{C}(-,V)$ is a sheaf for each $V\in X_{top}$.
Definition 4.1. Let $\mathcal{C}$, $\mathcal{D}$ be pre-pseudogroups on $X$. A morphism $f:\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}$ is a functor $f:\mathcal{C}\rightarrow\mathcal{D}$ preserving $X_{top}$. i.e. The following diagram is commutative: $\xymatrix{\mathcal{C}\ar[r]^{-}f&\mathcal{D}\\ X_{top}\ar@{=}[r]\ar[u]&X_{top}\ar[u]}$
Definition 2.1. Let $X$ be a $T_{1}$ space. A pre-pseudogroup on $X$ is a small category $\mathcal{C}$ with an embedding functor $X_{top}\subset\mathcal{C}$ satisfying the following: (1) $Ob(X_{top})=Ob(\mathcal{C})$. (2) $\mathcal{C}_{x}(V)\cong\displaystyle{\coprod_{y\in V}}\mathcal{C}_{x}^{y}$ for each open set $V\in X_{top}$ and each point $x\in X$, where the natural projections $\mathcal{C}_{x}^{y}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}_{x}(V)$ are identified with the natural injections $\mathcal{C}_{x}^{y}\rightarrow\displaystyle{\coprod_{y\in V}}\mathcal{C}_{x}^{y}$. (3) the category $\mathcal{C}^{\star}$ is a groupoid. A pseudogroup sheaf on $X$ is a pre-pseudogroup on $X$ satisfying the following: (4) the pre-sheaf $\mathcal{C}(-,V)$ is a sheaf for each $V\in X_{top}$.
Definition 3.1. A pseudogroup sheaf $\mathcal{C}$ on $X$ is concrete if the functor $\mathcal{C}\rightarrow Homeo^{l}_{X};f\mapsto\bar{f}$ is faithful.
Definition 5.1. Let $X$ be a smooth manifold. A pseudogroup sheaf $\mathcal{C}$ on $X$ is smooth if the underlying map $\bar{f}$ is smooth for any $f\in\mathcal{C}(U,V)$.
Definition 5.5. Let $X$ be a $T_{1}$ space. An $\mathcal{E}$-enriched pre-pseudogroup on $X$ is an $\mathcal{E}$-enriched category $\mathcal{C}$ with an $\mathcal{E}$-enriched functor $X_{top}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}$ satisfying the following: (1) $Ob(X_{top})=Ob(\mathcal{C})$. (2) $\mathcal{C}_{x}(V)\cong\displaystyle{\coprod_{y\in V}}\mathcal{C}_{x}^{y}$ for each open set $V\in X_{top}$ and each point $x\in X$, where the natural projections $\mathcal{C}_{x}^{y}\rightarrow\mathcal{C}_{x}(V)$ are identified with the natural injections $\mathcal{C}_{x}^{y}\rightarrow\displaystyle{\coprod_{y\in V}}\mathcal{C}_{x}^{y}$. (3) the $\mathcal{E}$-enriched category $\mathcal{C}^{\star}$ is an $\mathcal{E}$-enriched groupoid. A $\mathcal{E}$-enriched pseudogroup sheaf on $X$ is a pre-pseudogroup on $X$ satisfying the following: (4) the pre-sheaf $\mathcal{C}(-,V)$ is a sheaf for each $V\in X_{top}$.
Definition 2.3. Let ${J}\subset R$ be the radical of $R.$ The DG ideals $\mathsf{J}_{-}$ and $\mathsf{J}_{+}$ will be called internal and external DG radicals of DG algebra $\mathscr{R}.$
Definition 2.14. A finite-dimensional DG algebra $\mathscr{S}=(S,d_{\mathscr{S}})$ is called abstractly simple (or abstractly semisimple), if the underlying ungraded algebra $\underline{S}$ is simple (or semisimple).
Definition 1.12. A noncommutative scheme $\mathscr{X}=\mathscr{P}\!\mathit{erf}\!\operatorname{--}\mathscr{R}$ is called ${\Bbbk}$–smooth if the DG algebra $\mathscr{R}$ is perfect as the DG bimodule, i.e. as the DG module over $\mathscr{R}^{\circ}\otimes_{{\Bbbk}}\mathscr{R}.$
Definition 1.7. A semi-orthogonal decomposition of a triangulated category ${\mathcal{T}}$ is a sequence of full triangulated subcategories ${{\mathcal{N}}}_{1},\dots,{{\mathcal{N}}}_{n}$ in ${{\mathcal{T}}}$ such that there is an increasing filtration $0={\mathcal{T}}_{0}\subset{\mathcal{T}}_{1}\subset\cdots\subset{\mathcal{T}}_{% n}={\mathcal{T}}$ by left admissible subcategories for which the left orthogonals ${}^{\perp}{\mathcal{T}}_{r-1}$ in ${\mathcal{T}}_{r}$ coincide with ${\mathcal{N}}_{r}$ for all $1\leq r\leq n.$ in this case we write ${{\mathcal{T}}}=\left\langle{{\mathcal{N}}}_{1},\dots,{{\mathcal{N}}}_{n}% \right\rangle.$
Definition 1.14. Let $\mathscr{X}=\mathscr{P}\!\mathit{erf}\!\operatorname{--}\mathscr{R}$ and $\mathscr{Y}=\mathscr{P}\!\mathit{erf}\!\operatorname{--}\mathscr{S}$ be two derived noncommutative schemes and let $\mathsf{T}$ be a DG $\mathscr{S}\mbox{-}\mathscr{R}$–bimodule. A gluing $\mathscr{X}\underset{\mathsf{T}}{\oright}\mathscr{Y}$ of $\mathscr{X}$ and $\mathscr{Y}$ via (or with respect to) $\mathsf{T}$ is the DG category $\mathscr{P}\!\mathit{erf}\!\operatorname{--}\,(\mathscr{R}\underset{\mathsf{T}% }{\with}\mathscr{S}).$
Definition 1.1. The DG category of perfect DG modules $\mathscr{P}\!\mathit{erf}\!\operatorname{--}\mathscr{A}$ is the full DG subcategory of $\mathscr{P}(\mathscr{A})$ consisting of all DG $\mathscr{A}$–modules which are isomorphic to direct summands of objects from $\mathscr{S}\!\mathscr{F}_{fg}\!\operatorname{--}\!\mathscr{A}$ in the homotopy category ${{\mathcal{H}}^{0}}(\mathscr{P}(\mathscr{A}))\cong{\mathcal{D}}(\mathscr{A}).$
